ns</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: The figure is arbitrary; we do not know how they have arrived at it. Obviously, we are in the middle of the consultation</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">response</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> period, and we are asking for more information. Our view has been the same right the way through: in </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">certain cases, one rollover is too many</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">. It is about looking at affordability. Affordability is the question that should be asked, not the number of rollovers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Andy Lapointe</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">QuickQuid has a limit of two.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Henry Raine</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: T</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">his is </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">not the big issue, frankly, in terms of how the industry needs to be regulated.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q83 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Paul Blomfield:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12p